" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 271 "3.  Fundamental Theorem of Algebra.
  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra asserts that every non-constant p
olynomial (with complex-valued coefficients) has a root (a zero, a sol
ution).  A consequence of the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra is that e
very polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 270 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 13 " has exactl
y " }{TEXT 271 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 108 " roots.  An alternate formulation \+
of this consequence would be that every non-constant polynomial of deg
ree " }{TEXT 273 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 38 " can be factored into a product o
f a  " }{TEXT 272 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 16 " linear factors." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "Consider the followi
ng polynomials:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 6 "I.    " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "f := x^3-x^2-2*x" "6#>%\"fG,(*$%\"
xG\"\"$\"\"\"*$F'\"\"#!\"\"*&F+F)F'F)F," }{TEXT -1 9 "         " }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "factor (f) ;  " }}{PARA 11 "
" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%\"xG\"\"\",&F$F%F%F%F%,&F$F%\"\"#!\"\"F%" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 6 "II.   " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "g := 6*x^3+11*x^2+
6*x+1" "6#>%\"gG,**&\"\"'\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"$F(F(*&\"#6F(*$F*\"\"#F(F(*&
F'F(F*F(F(F(F(" }{TEXT -1 17 "                 " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "factor (g);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6
#*(,&*&\"\"#\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'F'F'F',&*&\"\"$F'F(F'F'F'F'F',&F(F'F'F'F'" 
}}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 7 "III.   " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "h := x^3-5*x+x
^2-5;" "6#>%\"hG,**$%\"xG\"\"$\"\"\"*&\"\"&F)F'F)!\"\"*$F'\"\"#F)F+F,
" }{TEXT -1 19 "                   " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "factor (h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%
