{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(H);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"\"\"#F&F&,&*&F'F&F%F&F&F&!\"\"F&" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 172 "Factor
 each polynomial and determine whether Maple was able to find enough l
inear factors to demonstrate the above assertion about the appropriate
 number of linear factors." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 650 "In those cases w
here Maple did not find enough linear factors, there is a reason why M
aple did not.  Maple makes an assumption that if the coefficients of a
 polynomial are all given exactly (as integers or rational numbers [ra
tios of integer]), then you are only interested in finding exact facto
rs (factors where the coefficients are integers or rational numbers). \+
 The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that the factors
 of  a polynomial will necessarily have the same kind of coefficients \+
as the polynomial, only the polynomial can be factored.  You can force
 Maple to report additional (approximate) factors.  For example,  comp
are:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"
xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 
"6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&\"\"#F&F&,&F%F&F'!\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 52 "What is t
he difference?  The extra-term is called a " }{TEXT 274 18 "field exte
nsion.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Adding it tells Maple to consider additonal f
actors where the coefficients are allowed to include elements from the
 field extension.  It is fairly clear from the factoriztion of " }
{TEXT 275 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " all by itself that something involving
  sqrt(5)  would have to be included.  However, there are problems whe
re there is not a obvious clue as to which specific field extension sh
ould be added.  If you are willing to accept an appropriate solution, \+
then using the field extension " }{TEXT 276 4 "real" }{TEXT -1 179 " t
ells Maple to factor the polynomial using a floating point approximati
on scheme.  For example, consider (here I am pretending I don't see th
at adding  sqrt(5) would be optimal):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "
" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F
&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(h,real);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+xz1OA!\"*F&F&,&F%F&
$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "Finally, the Fundamental Theorem of A
lgebra does not guarantee that a polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 277 1 "
n" }{TEXT -1 11 " will have " }{TEXT 278 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 " real lin
ear factors.  Rather, only hat it will have " }{TEXT 279 1 "n" }{TEXT 
-1 134 " linear factors.  What is the difference?  Some of the factors
 may involve complex roots rather than real roots.  For example compar
e:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(F);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"
xG\"\"\"F&!\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&F&F&F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,sqrt(3));" }}{PARA 8 "" 1 "" 
{TEXT -1 79 "Error, (in factor) 2nd argument, 2*3^(1/2), is not a vali
d algebraic extension\n" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "
factor(F,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+
++++5!\"*F&F&,&F%F&$F(F)!\"\"F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&F'F&F&" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,complex);" }}{PARA 11 "" 
