}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 380 "A related theorem about findin
g roots of polynomials (equivalently factoring polynomials into a prod
uct of linear factors) asserts that if the polynomial has real coeffic
ients -- all of the polynomials we have considered (and will consider)
 have had real coefficients -- then any complex roots (or factors) mus
t occur in conjugate pairs.  For example, both the complex factors of \+
" }{TEXT 282 5 "F, G " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }{TEXT 283 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 
236 "(above) all occurred in conjugate pairs.  Demonstrate this theore
m by creating three new polynomials, name them F1, G1 and H1, of degre
e 5, 6 and 7, resp., and show that the any complex factors of F1, G1 a
nd H1 occur in conjugate pairs." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 115 "For demonstration purposes it \+
